China’s shadow banking assets grew more than 20% in 2016 – to $9.7 trillion yuan. Now, countries with close trading ties to China are watching closely to see if it can curb the proliferation of risky investment products.

China’s leaders face a Catch 22: If they crack down on shadow banking, it could hurt economic growth and pose a challenge for the party. If they don’t crack down, they face the danger of a financial crisis that could spark upheaval.
For China’s Communist Party, a string of shadow banking defaults would pose a challenge to a regime that draws its legitimacy from a promise to the people of rising prosperity.
